00:14:04.570 --> 00:14:08.470
in the 1930's, a long, long, long,
long, long, long, long time ago.

00:14:08.470 --> 00:14:11.620
And that's where my
family's from, the South,

00:14:11.620 --> 00:14:13.780
so I wanted to write
about the South.

00:14:13.780 --> 00:14:16.320
And I also like things
like, things in England.

00:14:16.320 --> 00:14:21.830
Like when I was a little kid the
fantasy books I read were all these

00:14:21.830 --> 00:14:25.970
like British, English writers, so
I wanted to write a book like that.

00:14:25.970 --> 00:14:29.520
Kind of like to remember
my childhood.

00:14:29.520 --> 00:14:33.800
But that's where that came from.

00:14:36.820 --> 00:14:38.980
&gt;&gt; How did you find your publisher?

00:14:38.980 --> 00:14:42.730
&gt;&gt; Ronald L. Smith: How
did I find my publisher?

00:14:42.730 --> 00:14:46.620
Well, that's a really long
story and you can go online

00:14:46.620 --> 00:14:48.860
and you can find lots
of success stories.

00:14:48.860 --> 00:14:52.320
But the short version is I
worked very hard for a number

00:14:52.320 --> 00:14:55.740
of years on different stories.

00:14:55.740 --> 00:14:58.790
"Hoodoo" was my third
book but it's the one

00:14:58.790 --> 00:15:00.840
that got me signed by an agent.

00:15:00.840 --> 00:15:03.420
So these days you can
publish books on your own

00:15:03.420 --> 00:15:05.980
or you can find a traditional path.

00:15:05.980 --> 00:15:08.730 position:56%
I wanted to go the traditional route
so I kept working, and working,

00:15:08.730 --> 00:15:12.270
and working until I wrote a book
that got an agent's attention.

00:15:12.270 --> 00:15:16.410
And once it did, she
signed me as a client.

00:15:16.410 --> 00:15:19.460
And then, you know, the
agents, they know editors.

00:15:19.460 --> 00:15:22.570
So they send your book
to publishers.

00:15:22.570 --> 00:15:23.870
And I got really lucky.

00:15:23.870 --> 00:15:27.640
It was a dream come true because
"Hoodoo" as my first book went

00:15:27.640 --> 00:15:30.490
to auction so several
people wanted to buy it.

00:15:30.490 --> 00:15:33.190
So I was very lucky.

00:15:36.500 --> 00:15:38.480
&gt;&gt; Why did you like
drawing the pictures?

00:15:38.480 --> 00:15:40.120
&gt;&gt; Ronald L. Smith: What's that?

00:15:40.120 --> 00:15:43.500
&gt;&gt; Why did you like
drawing the pictures?

00:15:43.500 --> 00:15:44.800
&gt;&gt; Ronald L. Smith:
Well, I didn't get

00:15:44.800 --> 00:15:46.100
to draw the pictures in my books.

00:15:46.100 --> 00:15:50.060
The people who make the
book, the book company,

00:15:50.060 --> 00:15:53.290
they choose people
to draw the pictures.

00:15:53.290 --> 00:15:54.760
So my books are mostly words.

00:15:54.760 --> 00:15:56.060
Sometimes at the beginning

00:15:56.060 --> 00:15:57.940
of the chapter you might
see a little picture

00:15:57.940 --> 00:16:00.770
or the cover, like, has a picture.

00:16:00.770 --> 00:16:05.050
But the writer usually
just writes the words.

00:16:05.050 --> 00:16:06.350
Okay.

00:16:06.350 --> 00:16:12.960
&gt;&gt; Hi. How and why did you decide
to pursue a career in writing?

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:16.610
And what kept you going?

00:16:16.610 --> 00:16:17.910
&gt;&gt; Ronald L. Smith: Well,
that's a very good question.

00:16:17.910 --> 00:16:22.470
Well, from the time I was
your age I liked to write.

00:16:22.470 --> 00:16:25.710
I used to do the writing and my
brother used to do the drawings.

00:16:25.710 --> 00:16:27.800
So I would write and he would draw.

00:16:27.800 --> 00:16:30.930
And we would stay up
late creating stories.

00:16:30.930 --> 00:16:33.300
We stayed up so late my mom
and dad would bang on the door

00:16:33.300 --> 00:16:35.030
and tell us to go to sleep.

00:16:35.030 --> 00:16:37.500
So that's a pretty
good problem to have.

00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:39.970
But I like it so much
I just kept doing it.

00:16:39.970 --> 00:16:42.640
And then when I grew
up, I looked for a job

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:46.490
where I could use my writing skills
and that job was advertising.

00:16:46.490 --> 00:16:50.350
So I used to write commercials that
you've probably seen on TV before

00:16:50.350 --> 00:16:53.770
like McDonald's and a
bunch of other stuff.

00:16:53.770 --> 00:16:58.250 position:56%
But I got tired of writing that kind
of stuff so I really kept working

00:16:58.250 --> 00:17:02.360
on my books that whole time
and it finally paid off.

00:17:02.360 --> 00:17:03.690
But if you like to write,

00:17:03.690 --> 00:17:06.930
find as many opportunities
as you can to write.

00:17:06.930 --> 00:17:10.080
Whether it's for your school paper,
or for yourself, or your friends,

00:17:10.080 --> 00:17:11.860 position:56%
or whatever, just continue to do it.

00:17:11.860 --> 00:17:13.160
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:17:13.160 --> 00:17:14.460
&gt;&gt; Ronald L. Smith: You're welcome.

00:17:14.460 --> 00:17:17.710
&gt;&gt; How do you choose
your characters?

00:17:17.710 --> 00:17:19.010
&gt;&gt; Ronald L. Smith: How do I what?

00:17:19.010 --> 00:17:20.310
&gt;&gt; How do you choose
your characters?

00:17:20.310 --> 00:17:22.340 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Ronald L. Smith: They choose you.

00:17:22.340 --> 00:17:24.600
The character chooses you.

00:17:24.600 --> 00:17:27.400
They come around and they
tap you on the shoulder.

00:17:27.400 --> 00:17:30.040
And then you turn around
and they're gone.

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:34.580
But they whisper in your ear
what their name is sometimes.

00:17:34.580 --> 00:17:38.940
So that's a very kind of weird
way of saying you just make it up.

00:17:38.940 --> 00:17:42.470 position:56%
You know? Sometimes you say, "I want
to write about this kind of person,"

00:17:42.470 --> 00:17:44.660
or, "I want to write about
that kind of person."

00:17:44.660 --> 00:17:48.400
And they just kind of begin
to take a picture in your mind

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:51.860
and you just put it all together
and then they become a real person,

00:17:51.860 --> 00:17:54.920
at least in your head, sometimes.

00:17:54.920 --> 00:17:59.520
And then you can also talk to them
and people will think you're crazy

00:17:59.520 --> 00:18:04.370
but I talk to my characters
all the time.

00:18:04.370 --> 00:18:10.810 position:56%
&gt;&gt; How tiring is it to write a book?

00:18:10.810 --> 00:18:13.680
&gt;&gt; Ronald L. Smith: It's
a lot of work, yeah.

00:18:13.680 --> 00:18:14.980
It's a lot of work.

00:18:14.980 --> 00:18:16.300
It's very tiring.

00:18:16.300 --> 00:18:17.670
But it's worth it if you finish it.

00:18:17.670 --> 00:18:23.180
If you can get to the end,
then it's really worth it.

00:18:24.580 --> 00:18:30.170
&gt;&gt; How do you separate, how do
you know when to write dialog,

00:18:30.170 --> 00:18:32.680
then when to write narrative?

00:18:32.680 --> 00:18:33.980
&gt;&gt; Ronald L. Smith: Wow.

00:18:33.980 --> 00:18:37.280
So you've got all the right
words, dialog, narrative, plot.

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:39.250
Yeah. That's great.

00:18:39.250 --> 00:18:41.830
Well, you know, when you look
at any book in the bookstore

00:18:41.830 --> 00:18:43.770
or the library, you're
going to see dialog

00:18:43.770 --> 00:18:45.320
and you're going to
see the narrative.

00:18:45.320 --> 00:18:46.650
And you'll see that it's broken up.

00:18:46.650 --> 00:18:49.090
So you can't have a book
that's all dialog, right.

00:18:49.090 --> 00:18:51.310
You can't have a book
that's all description.

00:18:51.310 --> 00:18:54.360
So you have to find those places
where your characters talk.

00:18:54.360 --> 00:18:56.940
So you want to set the
scene and then you want

00:18:56.940 --> 00:18:58.530
to say one person says one thing.

00:18:58.530 --> 00:19:00.470
Another person says another thing.

00:19:00.470 --> 00:19:04.900
So it becomes natural because
you can't go on, and on,

00:19:04.900 --> 00:19:06.840
and on describing a car, right?

00:19:06.840 --> 00:19:09.000
You got to describe the
people in the car, too.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:13.250
And they're probably going to
talk so that's how you do it.

00:19:13.250 --> 00:19:18.070
&gt;&gt; Do you ever write
books for four year olds?

00:19:18.070 --> 00:19:19.370
&gt;&gt; Ronald L. Smith: Before?

00:19:19.370 --> 00:19:21.110
Did I ever write books before?

00:19:21.110 --> 00:19:23.440
&gt;&gt; For four year olds?

00:19:23.440 --> 00:19:24.740
&gt;&gt; Ronald L. Smith: Oh.

00:19:24.740 --> 00:19:26.580
Maybe one day.

00:19:26.580 --> 00:19:27.880
Maybe one day.

00:19:27.880 --> 00:19:30.710
That's got, I think
that's really hard.

00:19:30.710 --> 00:19:33.880
But there are lots of good
books for four year olds though.

00:19:35.600 --> 00:19:39.310
Okay. Any more?

00:19:39.310 --> 00:19:41.860
&gt;&gt; How many books have you written?

00:19:41.860 --> 00:19:43.160
&gt;&gt; Ronald L. Smith:
I've written two books.

00:19:43.160 --> 00:19:44.990
Well, I've actually
written a lot of books

00:19:44.990 --> 00:19:47.300
but I've only written two
books you can find in the store

00:19:47.300 --> 00:19:50.220
